{"cursor":"11536","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nThe 'Codex Alimentarius' (Latin for \"Book of Food\") is a collection of\ninternationally recognized standards, codes of practice, guidelines and other\nrecommendations relating to foods, food production and food safety.\n\nIts name is derived from the Codex Alimentarius\nAustriacus. [http://www.fao.org/docrep/v7700t/v7700t09.htm Codex\nAlimentarius: how it all began] Food and Agriculture Organization of the United\nNations website. Accessed 6 September 2012. Its texts are developed and\nmaintained by the 'Codex AlimentariusCommission', a body that was established in\nearly November 1961 by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United\nNations (FAO), was joined by the World Health Organization (WHO) in June 1962,\nand held its first session in Rome in October 1963. [http://www.codexalimentarius.org/about-codex/the-foundation-history-\nof-codex/en/ Codex timeline from 1945 to the present] The Commission's\nmain goals are to protect the health of consumers and ensure fair practices in\nthe international food trade. The Codex Alimentarius is recognized by the World\nTrade Organization as an international reference point for the resolution of\ndisputes concerning food safety and consumer protection. [http://www.wto.org/english/docs_e/legal_e/15sps_01_e.htm\nAgreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures] World Trade\nOrganization. Accessed 3 September 2008. [ftp://ftp-\n.fao.org/codex/Publications/understanding/Understanding_EN.pdf Understanding the\nCodex Alimentarius] Preface. Third Edition. Published in 2006 by the World\nHealth Organization and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United\nNations. Accessed 3 September 2008.\n\nCurrently (2012) the Codex Alimentarius Commission has: 186 Codex Members - 185\nMember Countries and 1 Member Organization (EU) 215 Codex Observers - 49 IGOs,\n150 NGOs, 16 UN.\n","linknr":263,"url":"Codex_Alimentarius_Commission","recor